        {
            "title": "CACI International Secures $73 Million U.S. Air Force Contract",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>\n  By Terell Wright </p><p>\n\n  CACI International has won a $73 million, five-year contract to continue its work modernizing the U.S. Air Force's integrated broadcast service. </p><!-- Article --><p>\n\n  The national security technology company said Thursday that the contract from the Defense Department will focus on upgrading the Air Force's network for transmitting time-sensitive tactical and strategic intelligence and targeting data across multiple domains, including air, ground and space, for the Defense Department and U.S. allies. </p><p>\n\n  The contract will support the Integrated Broadcast Services-Network Services, which are used to transmit intelligence for the Air Force electronically. </p><p>\n\n  CACI Chief Executive John Mengucci said the company's software-defined solutions that broaden the Air Force's network capabilities will bolster the nation's national security and allow it to maintain superiority. </p><p>\n\n  Write to Terell Wright at terell.wright@wsj.com </p><br/><p>\n  (END) Dow Jones Newswires</p><p>\n\n  10-02-25 1647ET</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/caci-international-secures-73-million-u-s-air-force-contract-ce7d5bdede80f125",
            "pub_date": "2025-10-03 04:50:34",
            "source": "marketscreener",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
        {
            "title": "Sept. Planned Job Additions Weakest Since 2011",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><div class=\"akcelo-wrapper akcelo-video media--169\" style=\"width:100%\"><div class=\"border:solid 1px #C0C0C0\" id=\"Zonebourse_Article_Video\" video-id=\"k7H02epmfGD28DDXGpy\"><div itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"https://schema.org/VideoObject\"><meta content=\"Sept. Planned Job Additions Weakest Since 2011\" itemprop=\"name\"/><meta content=\"US employers dialed back hiring plans in September and announced fewer job cuts, according to data from outplacement firm Challenger, Gray &amp; Christmas. Companies last month announced plans to add 117,313 jobs, down 71% from a year earlier and marking the weakest September for hiring intentions since 2011. The report released Thursday noted a significant slowdown in seasonal hiring plans compared to years past.\nThe report shows a labor market in which there is both limited hiring and firing. Bloomberg's Michael McKee joined Carol Massar and Tim Stenovec on 'Bloomberg Businessweek Daily' to break down the report.\n\n\" itemprop=\"description\"/><meta content=\"2025-10-02T22:45:23+02:00\" itemprop=\"uploadDate\"/><meta content=\"/images/mtnewswires/A3469336.png\" itemprop=\"thumbnailUrl\"/><meta content=\"https://geo.dailymotion.com/player/x80uo.html?video=k7H02epmfGD28DDXGpy\" itemprop=\"embedUrl\"/></div></div></div>\n               US employers dialed back hiring plans in September and announced fewer job cuts, according to data from outplacement firm Challenger, Gray &amp; Christmas. Companies last month announced plans to add 117,313 jobs, down 71% from a year earlier and marking the weakest September for hiring intentions since 2011. The report released Thursday noted a significant slowdown in seasonal hiring plans compared to years past.<p>\nThe report shows a labor market in which there is both limited hiring and firing. Bloomberg's Michael McKee joined Carol Massar and Tim Stenovec on 'Bloomberg Businessweek Daily' to break down the report.</p><!-- Article --><p><span class=\"js-l-obf link link--blue\" data-lobf=\"v4fox4ar=NTQyQxJmBMKwpP7nl8C=BbKwgTpvkfAwLuu\" data-tobf=\"blank\" onclick=\"gaEvent('Out', 'mtnewswires', '51247943');\">Bloomberg videos</span>, provided by MT Newswires</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/sept-planned-job-additions-weakest-since-2011-ce7d5bdede80f327",
